. Accordingly, the Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative (APTII) of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office has been working to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7cebb8d9-5d38-434b-baad-28d7b7817d91": {"__data__": {"id_": "7cebb8d9-5d38-434b-baad-28d7b7817d91", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "79cf51947f776451cbe73df04a0dc6cc2140e156fa32b897d78d9d9967dfa823"}}, "hash": "79cf51947f776451cbe73df04a0dc6cc2140e156fa32b897d78d9d9967dfa823", "text": "develop new approaches and strategies designed to help align trade dynamics with the objectives of poverty reduction and human development in the Asia Pacific region. Since its founding in 2002, the APTII has promoted innovative research and policy advice that seeks to define clear substantive linkages between trade and human development, and that is consistent with the objective of supporting the Millennium De- velopment Goals (MDGs). The APTII, striving to build on its previous work and achievements in this third and current phase of its work programme (2008-2011), aspires to make a significant contribution to policy dialogues by fostering re- gional trade and investment regimes that are consistent with human development goals in the region. A cen- tral challenge facing policy-makers is to facilitate patterns of inclusive regional integration that enable them to address specific development priorities and goals, particularly with reference to the development needs of least developed countries (LDCs), landlocked developing countries (LLDCs), and small island developing states (SIDS). The focus of APTII\u2019s current work programme, therefore, is on: 1) enhancing trade competitive- ness and capacity development to formulate employment-responsive and gender-responsive trade policies; and 2) strengthening the capacity to implement pro-poor regional integration strategies, including through key regional processes and/or mechanisms. In line with this focus, APTII will publish a series of studies and discussion papers highlighting the policy implications of the multifaceted dimensions of current trade trends and patterns, as well as their human development impact in the Asia Pacific region. vi Preface With the spread and deepening of the global financial crisis across the world, a number of issues are likely to be intensely debated in the coming months and years. Policy makers in the Asia Pacific region for instance need to think creatively about national, regional and global policy options addressing the inherent vulner- abilities in the region arising on account of the current nature and pattern of production and international trade in goods and services. The emergence of China and India as major regional and global economic powers, the dynamics un- leashed in its wake and the possible impact of the two economies on the rest of the countries in the region has been an issue of central interest and importance to policy makers in the region. The Policy Paper, The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India, by Emel Memi\u015f, attempts to provide an analytical framework, and carries out an empirical assessment of the recent patterns of growth, trade and investment flows in Asia with a special emphasis on China and India. The study argues that the trade structure of countries in Asia is undergoing a change with the emergence of China and India as major economic powers, and that neighbouring countries are likely to face opportunities and/or challenges, depending on their current industrial structure. While examining the current import patterns of China and India, the Policy Paper has highlighted that countries which export highly sophisticated products are more likely to benefit from the growth dynamism in these two countries, and there may not be significant opportunities for countries whose exports comprise of low value added products. It has been argued that for neighbouring developing countries to overcome their challenges, strong domestic demand for local production would be the key to their successful integration into regional development, as domestic demand generates motivation for domestic investment and attracts high-quality, pro-trade FDI. Such a policy also assumes salience for overcoming some of the challenges on account of the ongoing global economic crisis. The findings in many ways echo the results of the previous APTII Policy Paper on South-South Regionalism and Trade Cooperation in the Asia-Pacific Region. From a policy perspective, the Policy Paper underscores the point that for countries to benefit from the current trading patterns in the region, they need to focus on an integrated approach to trade, industrial and social policy and argues further that it may be useful to evaluate regional integration arrangements on the basis of their potential impacts on industrial development at the sectoral level. It is our hope that this study will prove useful to governments, UNDP country offices, research institu- tions, civil society organizations, and other stakeholders in the Asia-Pacific region in furthering the debate on regional industrial development strategies in Asia. Omar Noman Chief of Policies and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo vii This paper was written under contract with the Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office. While taking full responsibility for all the views and analyses expressed in this paper, the author gratefully acknowledges", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "58c71d30-41d6-40ef-8ab0-41dae5c99873": {"__data__": {"id_": "58c71d30-41d6-40ef-8ab0-41dae5c99873", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b255e4f96d1325bfc6c9f2b6b4f226d09d3de84d457117a80423d4da01775624"}, "3": {"node_id": "46fd118c-2b41-4f1f-bb58-2068cd2ac9e0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "13346c6261859664b58706571ea469f779477d203c738328dbf5dc456aba85df"}}, "hash": "e250e6e282ebe60af8b1c04d40708fcf9722e4e9b3bfc96c0b8ade2ca40b8199", "text": "the suggestions made by an anonymous referee on an earlier version of the paper, as well as Manuel F. Montes, Biplove Choudhary, Yumiko Yamamoto, Kamal Malhotra, Rajah Rasiah, Chatrini Weeratunge and members of the Knowledge Resources Review Committee, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office. Professional editing by John Tessitore is gratefully acknowledged. Acknowledgements viii Abbreviations and acronyms AEC Asian Economic Community ASEAN Association of South East Asian Nations ASEAN-4 Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippines, Thailand BTAs Bilateral Trade Agreements DPR of Korea Democratic People\u2019s Republic of Korea FDI Foreign Direct Investment First-Tier Hong-Kong Special Administrative Region of China, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan, Province of China FG Flying Geese GDP Gross Domestic Product Lao PDR Lao People\u2019s Democratic Republic NICs Newly Industrialized Countries NIEs Newly Industrialized Economies OECD Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development PoC Province of China PPP Purchasing Power Parity RCA Revealed Comparative Advantage RTAs Regional Trade Agreements SAR Special Administrative Region SC Country Sophistication Second-Tier Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand SITC Standard International Trade Classification SP Product Sophistication TNC Transnational Company UN United Nations UNCTAD United Nations Conference on Trade and Development UNDP United Nations Development Programme WDI World Development Indicators WIR World Investment Report ix This study attempts to evaluate the potential for cooperative regional industrial development strategies in Asia, including the implications of growth, trade, and investment flows, with a special emphasis on China and India. The results indicate that, based on Flying Geese (FG)-consistent patterns in trade structures over the last decade in the region, opportunities exist for developing nations to benefit from increasing trade and investment opportunities in the context of the growing absorption capacities of China and India. Some schol- ars have argued that should these two economies proceed and expand in tandem, they will provide growth leverage both for their neighbours and economies elsewhere through a web of supply chains. However, these opportunities also involve policy challenges for the slower-growing economies that are following China and India. Exploring the changes in the structure of China\u2019s and India\u2019s imports, the study highlights that countries exporting highly sophisticated products are likely to benefit more from the growth of these two emerging economies. In the framework of the study, it is seen that for the slow-growing potential successors barring the more advanced economies and exporters of higher levels of sophistication such as the Philippines and Viet Nam, there are no significant opportunities if the current patterns of regional trade integration are to persist. Compared to the earlier successors of Japan and the Republic of Korea, the transfer of labour-intensive start-up industries from China and India to other countries might take a longer time given the huge labour reserve of these two populous nations. The study also discusses the policy responses that Asian producer and exporter countries of labour-intensive goods should undertake to have enhanced benefits from the regional integration process. Developing nations should consider the improvement of trade facilitation and underlying frameworks which drives regional integration and growth. Attention has been raised to a lack of an institutional base that strengthens and supports the regional integration process focusing on the promotion of economic develop- ment within the region. The study suggests that there is a significant role for regional trade agreements (RTAs) and bilateral trade agreements (BTAs) in the facilitation of regional division of labour thereby opening up new possibilities for slower-growing nations. However, these agreements should be evaluated considering the possible positive and/or negative impacts on industrial development from a regional development perspec- tive, rather than the standard static approaches usually implemented. Assessments on the changes in trade volume that ignore industrial transformation through domestic or foreign investment are incomplete, and do not capture the synergies among trade, investment, and development, which have important implications for the FG pattern of development in a regional context. Attention is needed to ensure a socially cohesive progress and an approach to free trade in its larger context including its social costs. Even though international links and trade related policies are deeply significant in order to benefit from regional division of labour, historical evidence tells us that we should not downplay the role of public policy. One cannot dismiss the fact that a robust domestic economy with its external trade policy depends Executive summary x particularly on achievements in social development.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "46fd118c-2b41-4f1f-bb58-2068cd2ac9e0": {"__data__": {"id_": "46fd118c-2b41-4f1f-bb58-2068cd2ac9e0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b255e4f96d1325bfc6c9f2b6b4f226d09d3de84d457117a80423d4da01775624"}, "2": {"node_id": "58c71d30-41d6-40ef-8ab0-41dae5c99873", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e250e6e282ebe60af8b1c04d40708fcf9722e4e9b3bfc96c0b8ade2ca40b8199"}}, "hash": "13346c6261859664b58706571ea469f779477d203c738328dbf5dc456aba85df", "text": "Even though trade-centred development is necessary for regional development, it cannot be sufficient if not supported by the latter. Since industrial upgrading, in- novation, technological capacity, and human capabilities are interwoven with each other in a FG-framework, social, industrial, or trade related policies cannot be taken as totally separate factors. Rather, all three policies should be", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c0616854-2be3-46c2-b4d6-c575381b6565": {"__data__": {"id_": "c0616854-2be3-46c2-b4d6-c575381b6565", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ed2606b2cf389cfe96e4631d517e5d7e063d369f7bd195b49d2a2c42e91eb412"}}, "hash": "ed2606b2cf389cfe96e4631d517e5d7e063d369f7bd195b49d2a2c42e91eb412", "text": "considered within an inclusive holistic structure. Recent shifts in the structure of production within the region through product fragmentation can enable slower-growing economies to reap the benefits of being part of these dynamic international net- works facilitating reinvestment of the profits in other domestic industries. Should the institutional settings be such as to provide available opportunities through an integrated trade and industrial policy framework the fragmentation of production processes can possibly confer possible gains for all. However, one cannot conclude fragmentation is good without any conditionality. Suffice it to say that the challenges are vast for the economies hosting the production of low value-added parts and pieces of the final good produced. Being locked into the labour-intensive phases of production may result in investors\u2019 perception of the host countries as low-wage labour reserves. Unless participating in international production networks facilitates job creation and capital formation and strengthens the balance of payments of that economy, the value-added created in such activities is usually transferred outside the host country through the operations of multinational firms. Rising foreign direct investment (FDI) flows among economies in the region throw up new possibili- ties for regional development. Yet, it is important that corresponding FDIs be pro-trade with backward and forward linkages with domestic industries in order to provide opportunities for the hosting countries to boost their accumulation of capital as well as extend their existing innovative capabilities. Neither rising exports of manufacturing nor FDI have always been accompanied with economic growth. Overdependence on foreign resources for domestic capital accumulation may not always enable the receiving country to receive the investment in particular sectors of industry. Industrialization which depends on domestic market expansion can be a better strategy in a rapidly integrating world. The significance of domestic demand with respect to domestic investment in capital accumulation is critical for a FG pattern of development. Growth in domestic demand proves to be a strong policy for rising employment as well. Finally, this study asserts that the evolution of a FG pattern requires a holistic policy approach to regional integration through trade, industrialization, and, hence, development. In addition, the criteria for receiving high-quality FDI inflows must include qualitative measures along with existing quantitative measures. Criteria such as knowledge intensity and provisioning of resources for innovation have formed new policy measures for FDI. High-quality FDI is critical for enabling a country to join the FG pattern of development. 1 Cooperative strategies in regional integration based on trade and international investment flows have turned out to be very important for the sustainability of region-wide development. The famous analogy between the flying pattern of wild geese and empirical observations on the formation of regional industrialization in Asia was introduced to the development literature by Kaname Akamatsu as early as the 1930s. The flying geese (FG) pattern of development involves a process of regional integration through which industries in advanced countries are adopted in less advanced countries, creating an international division of labour that resembles the cooperative interdependence implicit in the inverse V-pattern of flying geese.1 In this framework, coun- tries with technologically advanced industries are followed by successor2 economies with less advanced industries. In an idealized form, all countries move forward together in an orderly fashion. A number of studies looking at the regional industrial development patterns in Asian economies over the last six decades have pointed to evidence consistent with the FG pattern of development. In these analy- ses, Japan primarily plays the role of a leading goose. First-tier countries, consisting of Hong Kong, Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, the Republic of Korea, Singapore, and Taiwan, Province of China (PoC), are succeeded by the second-tier countries of Indonesia, Malaysia, and Thailand, and, finally, by the recently emerging countries, such as China and Viet Nam, in the order of their level of industrial sophistication. Within the emerging economies, the recent rise of China and India has initiated significant debates in international political and economic arenas. Scholars have been asking whether China and India will become comrades or competitors with the rest of the region (Ahearne et al. 2003, 2006; Xing 2007; De Castro 2006; Kui 2006; Kwan 2002). Will this recent development disrupt the presumed FG pattern of development? Have China and India caught up with more advanced countries and become leading geese? If so, do they create either opportunities or obstacles to the development of other developing countries in the region? This study aims to provide a useful basis for a potentially revamped FG framework in Asia, and it discusses the possible opportunities and challenges for the other developing nations in the region posed by emerging China", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a70bbe0a-2c4c-4c8c-8760-5ad7b8942246": {"__data__": {"id_": "a70bbe0a-2c4c-4c8c-8760-5ad7b8942246", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8e48958e97f7d86c9808a9a7b2192b0195370029c5927ee64fcb3f0624330c44"}}, "hash": "8e48958e97f7d86c9808a9a7b2192b0195370029c5927ee64fcb3f0624330c44", "text": "and India. It is important to point out that the question of whether the FG framework constitutes a theory of development or simply describes an empirical observation has not been resolved in the literature. There is no consensus as to whether the FG pattern of development only describes particular shifts in the industrial structure of a country relative to its regional partners at a specific point in time, or it is a genuine \u2018theory\u2019 of industrial development that can be applied repeatedly. Looking at Akamatsu\u2019s original argument, it is possible 1. Introduction 1 The conceptual framework of the FG pattern of development in Asia and critiques of FG framework are summarized in Annex A. 2 To avoid analytical confusion and misinterpretation, we use the term \u201csuccessor\u201d instead of the more often-used term \u201cfollower\u201d for countries that are technologically less advanced. The use of the term \u201csuccessor\u201d or \u201cfollower\u201d in this literature is not meant to describe such countries are being geopolitically subordinate to countries with more advanced industries. In our view, regional cooperative patterns of industrial development are not automatic outcomes of market relations (which in earlier times were also imposed by colonial supremacy) but instead require strategic policy interventions by all countries involved. 2 to argue that the FG framework does not provide a complete theory of development, i.e., the FG framework is not an attempt to explain the underlying factors behind a particular economy\u2019s advancement. To put it differently, based on our reading of Akamatsu (1962) we believe that the reasons why one or another country is associated with the leading goose is not pinpointed by the FG framework; rather, the framework provides an empirical pattern that sheds light on the development dynamics of a region. This study discusses the FG pattern of development as a description of the changes in industrial structure that have important implica- tions in employment patterns as well as the productivity level of members of a society. We take the view that, beyond empirical patterns, strategic policy choices are indispensable in understanding the spread of regional industrial development. The position of the countries in the FG formation is not perfectly fixed like the flying pattern of wild geese; rather, the ranking of countries has a dynamic nature that changes over time. In this study we aim to provide a framework that can be used to evaluate trade outcomes within an industrial development perspec- tive that can be considered as the first step in impact assessments. We implement an empirical method that enables us to perform a dynamic analysis that indicates shifts in the advancement level of an economy within the region. We calculate the average sophistication level of exported goods by nations in terms of technologi- cal content, which we call \u201ccountry sophistication.\u201d Country sophistication informs us on the relative position of nations within a region. We then evaluate our results introducing a framework (using S-shaped curves) that recasts the FG pattern, deriving some important policy implications in terms of opportunities and challenges, from a FG perspective, based on our empirical analysis. The historical evidence regarding the FG pattern of development also indicates major shifts in the trends of economic growth, trade, and investment patterns in each country group (Akamatsu 1962; Tung 2007). Accordingly, our specific objectives also involve an as- sessment of this historical evidence, looking for similar patterns in economic growth, trade, and investment among the nations of the region, with a particular emphasis on the emerging economies. The focus of the current study is limited to the question of the potentials and challenges of a revamped FG pattern of development in Asia. The FG framework not only provides a useful perspective to evaluate changes in the industrial structure of an economy but also can be helpful in evaluating regional and bilat- eral trade agreements from an industrial development perspective. Industrial development per se enhances the employment, productivity, and capabilities of the members of a society if buttressed by the required social programs in health and education. A human development approach to regional development must pay particular attention to the impact of industrial development on empowerment, productivity, equity, and sustainability3. If human development is the goal, shifts in industrial structure should be evaluated as to whether they generate new employment, help eradicate poverty, or enhance people\u2019s well-being. The specific application of the FG framework in this study can be considered as an initial step in analyzing trade from an industrial development perspective. However, further research is required to investigate the human develop- ment impact of a potential FG pattern of development in the region. The main conclusions of this", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "262db670-107f-4ca0-9075-b1116f7e1b35": {"__data__": {"id_": "262db670-107f-4ca0-9075-b1116f7e1b35", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "292aff7ad9df7113908fa825821fe3ac650cb5956793ed19b7393d01dbcae3c2"}}, "hash": "292aff7ad9df7113908fa825821fe3ac650cb5956793ed19b7393d01dbcae3c2", "text": "study can be summarized as follows: \uf06c Our results demonstrate a FG-consistent evolution in Asia over the last decade. We observe FG-predicted shifts in country sophistication, particularly for countries where we observe major changes in growth, trade, and investment patterns. \uf06c The pace at which Japan or the first-tier countries transformed their place in the regional division of labour may not be relevant in the case of China or India. Rather, it might take a long time for China and India to move away from production of less sophisticated products, the majority of which correspond to the export goods of other less technologically advanced developing countries, due to the sheer sizes 3 See Memi\u015f and Montes (2005) for a more detailed discussion of these facets of human development and a human development approach to trade. 3 of the two economies. Further, export concentrations in terms of destination are observed among some developing countries in lower technological ranks, which might signal possible difficult development challenges for these countries. However, there exists significant potential if less developed countries are able to benefit fully from the growing absorption capacities of China and India. \uf06c The import patterns of China and India show that the shares of highly sophisticated products have risen. This provides promising evidence for growth externalities for countries that are exporters of these products, i.e., first and second-tier nations. What should be the policy responses of the followers? \uf06c Facilitate agreed specialization in regional trade agreements or bilateral trade arrangements with lead- ing geese. Any trade agreement either at the regional or bilateral level should be evaluated in terms of the possible positive and/or negative affects on industrial development from a FG-type development perspective. \uf06c In order to achieve cooperative regional industrial development through foreign-direct investment (FDI), high-quality pro-trade FDI is required. FDI should enable a country to take part in international production networks that support job creation, capital formation and improve the country\u2019s balance of payments; otherwise, the value produced domestically is only to the advantage of external parties. \uf06c The process of regional integration, being part of an international production network, should be assessed not only by quantitative measures but also by qualitative measures, such as the effect of a unit of FDI on economic growth, employment, skill enhancement, or on the competitiveness of local enterprises. \uf06c Domestic demand as well as external demand plays an important role in a FG-consistent development pattern. Overdependence on foreign resources through exports implicitly assumes that external de- mand will always exist. In addition, when foreign resources are available, they may not be directed to the industries that need these resources most. Domestic demand matters for achieving economic growth, and the increasing size of domestic demand establishes the motivation for domestic as well as foreign investment. \uf06c A holistic approach to development at the regional level is needed for the sustainable economic devel- opment of the successor countries. Any trade or investment policy should be accompanied and led by an industrial and public policy. This study is presented in the four sections. The following section investigates recent trends in the trade and investment patterns of Asian countries over the last two decades. Section 3 provides a recast of a FG framework within a regional development context and summarizes the empirical findings. Section 4 presents possible policy outcomes suggested by the empirical analysis and discusses the scope for development- oriented cooperative regional integration. The last section concludes with the main findings of this study and some suggestions for further research. 4 The historical evidence regarding Japan\u2019s economic development since World War II establishes four facts on FG-consistent economic growth, trade, and investment trends: a) Japan experienced enormous economic growth during this period \u2014 the highest in the world during the 1950s and 1960s. b) Japan\u2019s exports and imports have grown at significant rates. Japan\u2019s share in world exports rose from 4 percent during the 1960s to 8 percent in 2000. The yearly growth of imports increased from 4 percent on average during the 1980s to 9.5 percent since 2000. c) Japan\u2019s major trading partners and countries that have received the majority of Japanese FDI have been located within the nearby Asia-Pacific region. d) The range of income levels of Japan\u2019s partner economies is much broader than those of countries that are trade or investment partners of other integrated regions, such as the European Union and North America. In this regard, we look at recent trends in economic growth, trade, and investment in Asia to see if there have been shifts in the regional division of labour. 2.1 GDP growth trends Despite the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2ffa7054-fc38-4021-93f7-ddc7dc3543e3": {"__data__": {"id_": "2ffa7054-fc38-4021-93f7-ddc7dc3543e3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "288e3cc1eb5c04200ab414551df790499a56bc36026a1c1645ee8dcf44423957"}, "3": {"node_id": "bdd1fdec-2cf3-4cd1-9a89-93114bcc965d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cf01a409924b41356a39968529dce5bd12b3780cd75c1cc13c7464e11b22a42d"}}, "hash": "7c69930b1d17fdc3193ce937556e58d810d87c44d53b4ecc0353bf22a3573c57", "text": "financial crisis of the 1990s, growth performance of Asian economies has been impressive (see Figure 2.1). Annual average growth rates of GDP per capita for all sub-regions in Asia show enormous success when compared to the global average, and these high economic growth rates have been sustained over a long period. In the East Asia and Pacific region, for example, with the exception of the crisis years the growth rate has been at least three times higher than the world average. Furthermore, China\u2019s growth rates have been even higher; and India\u2019s growth was not disrupted during the 1990s, resulting in uninterrupted progress over the decade. 2. Recent trends in growth, investment, and trade patterns in Asia 5 Figure 2.1 GDP per capita growth (annual average %) Source: See Annex Table B1. In every decade after World War II there have been sustained episodes of rapid growth in at least one Asian economy when there was no other region with similar records (Tung 2007; World Bank 1993). As noted earlier, in the 1950s and 1960s the Japanese economy reached the highest growth rates in the world. In the 1970s first-tier Asian economies replaced Japan; and since the 1980s the highest growth rates have shifted to China. High-growth rates over the last decade show FG-consistent trends. These prolonged periods of economic growth have been the subject of a long debate in the literature. Scholars have asked why and how these Asian countries managed to maintain high growth rates and why this pattern was not observed elsewhere. The two pillars of these sustained episodes of growth are proposed as trade and FDI. The following sections will focus on these dimensions. 2.2 Expansion of external trade Similar to economic growth, trade growth rates in all Asia sub-regions stand much above the global average (Figures 2.2 and 2.3). Growth rates in Chinese exports have been unique over the last decade. For the period 2001-2006 we observe a declining trend in global imports and exports but a rising trend in all sub-regions in Asia. In the case of China, the annual growth rate of exports and imports for 2001-2006 are approximately 25 and 20 percent, respectively. 6 Figure 2.2 Export growth of goods and services (annual average %) Source: See Annex Table B1. Figure 2.3 Import growth of goods and services (annual average %) Source: See Annex Table B1. 7 In addition to the growth rate, the direction of trade also matters for an examination of consistency with FG predictions. The export matrices of the region with destination countries are displayed below. Table 2.1 shows FG-consistent patterns of trade in the region. The share of China as a destination country rose in the exports of almost all countries. This indicates the growing significance of China as an importer of goods, especially from relatively advanced countries in the region such as Japan, the Republic of Korea, and second- tier economies, implying that China\u2019s growing imports consist more of high-tech intermediate capital goods. On the other hand, the share of Chinese exports to some of the first and second-tier countries, namely the Republic of Korea, Indonesia, and Malaysia, increased from 1994 to 2003, whereas Japan\u2019s share declined, indicating that China\u2019s role has been changing in the family of successor geese. India\u2019s share as a destination country also rose in terms of exports of all countries, other than Japan (which remained flat), even though the rate of increase is slower compared to that of China. Particularly, India\u2019s share in exports from Nepal and Sri Lanka showed a significant increase, accounting for 52.4 percent and 5.0 percent total exports, respectively. The share of neighbouring countries in India\u2019s exports also increased slightly from 1994 to 2003. In summary, evidence displayed in this section shows FG-consistent shifts in the region\u2019s trade structure, particularly the rising significance of China and India, which have large domestic markets and have became important trading partners of the regional economies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bdd1fdec-2cf3-4cd1-9a89-93114bcc965d": {"__data__": {"id_": "bdd1fdec-2cf3-4cd1-9a89-93114bcc965d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emer