ollowed by Singapore and India. Since 2004 the inward FDI performance indexes of China and India have risen, while those of Indonesia and Thailand have declined. In the case of China, the share of FDI inflows of total investment has been quite stagnant in the range of 8 to 10 percent since 2000. This observation contradicts the argument raised rather frequently that China\u2019s economic growth owes much to the increasing size of FDI inflows. Although FDI inflows into China are quite high in absolute terms, their share in total investment remains stable and does not correspond to the majority of total investment in the country.5 In general, FDI inflows in the region suggest a pattern in keeping with the FG framework. Table 2.3 shows that FDI outflows as a percentage of total investment increased overall. According to UNCTAD (2007), the rise has been at a rate of more than 50 percent in 2006; and the largest sources of FDI in the region in 2006 were China and India, which is FG-consistent. A rising trend is shared particularly by the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e30251fb-52a1-47a1-ae94-12fdff0b5089": {"__data__": {"id_": "e30251fb-52a1-47a1-ae94-12fdff0b5089", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potentia