71dac6049015", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "682b6e9e5ddee6b6067d5d005fee77ff49c32955782560bf23243c071e6f4291"}}, "hash": "ddbe72ebe42887caf05708f95a41d5737a913ccc282d467bd845cbc9cab89e0a", "text": "1.0 0.9 0.5 0.7 Indonesia 0.0 -0.0 0.5 0.4 0.5 0.5 6.2 4.5 3.9 Lao PDR .. 0.2 2.3 -0.3 .. 0.0 .. .. .. Malaysia 2.6 0.9 8.8 1.2 8.6 6.0 8.5 11.4 20.1 Philippines 1.0 0.2 0.8 -1.1 0.5 2.3 4.1 1.3 0.6 Singapore 2.0 17.1 20.9 77.9 10.3 12.1 31.5 19.3 28.3 Thailand 0.0 0.4 -0.1 1.6 0.6 1.8 0.2 1.1 1.3 Viet Nam .. .. .. .. .. .. .. 0.4 0.4 Source: UNCTAD key data from WIR Annex tables. www.unctad.org/Templates/Page.asp?intItemID=3277&lang=1 In addition to the changes in the ratio of FDI flows to total investment, it is important to look at the destination of the FDI flows from advanced countries into neighbouring nations. The share of Asian countries as recipients of Japan\u2019s investments has increased since 1981 (Table 2.4). Shares of first and second-tier coun- tries slightly increased over the two decades 1985 to 2005; and China has been a major recipient of Japan\u2019s FDI since 1995, growing to 40 percent in 2005. India\u2019s share doubled in 2005 compared to the previous year, but in terms of overall size this seems negligible compared to China\u2019s share. Similar changes in the structure of FDI outflows were seen in the Republic of Korea for the period 1985- 2004 (Table 2.5). The share of recipient countries shows that Malaysia and Indonesia were the major recipients of the Republic of Korea\u2019s investment in the region during the period 1985-1990. However, from 1995 onward the share of these ASEAN (Association of South East Asian Nations) countries declined, whereas the Republic of Korea\u2019s FDI into China rapidly increased, and China quickly became the top recipient of the Republic of Korea\u2019s investment in 1995. In 2004, 57 percent of the Republic of Korea\u2019s outward FDI went to Asia, and more than two-thirds of that investment went to China. 13 Developing countries such as Cambodia, Lao PDR, Mongolia, and Sri Lanka currently receive only a very small percentage of both Japan\u2019s and the Republic of Korea\u2019s FDI. This suggests that they are not likely successor countries to China and India, an observation confirmed by recent figures on China\u2019s FDI outflows6 (Table 2.6)7. A comparison of China\u2019s FDI structure with those of Japan and the Republic of Korea reveals a dif- ferent picture in terms of destination. However, whether this is sufficient to argue that FDI figures show a FG-consistent character or not is unclear. In order to make a more robust comparison we need data over a longer time period for China; thus, it might be too early to make a conclusion. Yet, Hong and Sun (2004) argue that the composition of recipient countries of China\u2019s FDI outflows is quite similar to that of the Republic of Korea during the period 1988-2002, and to Japan\u2019s outflows twenty years ago, in the period 1968-1982, targeting resource-rich regions and countries in Latin America and Africa. These facts are also confirmed by the figures presented in Table B.3. Given the recent developments in economic growth and trade flows within the region, we argue that empirical trends provide supporting evidence for an existing FG pattern of develop- ment to a major degree. The expansion of FDI inflows into the region, as well as the rising trade flows out of and into emerging economies, signifies FG-consistent patterns. The recent expansion of FDI and trade flows indicates the shifts in the production structure. Since the 1990s the expansion in cross-border production sharing, the disintegration of production activities, and fragmentation \u2014 that is, the production of a part or parts of a larger component (particularly in the manufacturing sector) \u2014 have been more apparent.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f240d924-9fb5-46ca-9d34-71dac6049015": {"__data__": {"id_": "f240d924-9fb5-46ca-9d34-71dac6049015", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ed09c642eb8b0f83f7207d177c33452c9ebd405d6b3ae6e3af1b6e1a7eebcb5e"}, "2": {"node_id": "e2e91653-d564-4ace-bd7b-9ee1d70118da", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ddbe72ebe42887caf05708f95a41d5737a913ccc282d467bd845cbc9cab89e0a"}}, "hash": "682b6e9e5ddee6b6067d5d005fee77ff49c32955782560bf23243c071e6f4291", "text": "At the same time, 