r-income developing neighbors? To answer this question, we need to look at trade and investment at more disaggregated levels in each country. The type of industries that are significant in a particular country\u2019s trade might also inform us as to the country\u2019s role in the regional division of labour and its evolution. In order to find a benchmark description that we can utilize, we go back to the original 1962 study by Akamatsu. 3.1 Empirical methods The underpinning mechanism of the FG framework involves the transfer of certain industries from more advanced countries to less developed economies of the region, which occurs with industrial upgrading (Aka- matsu\u2019s first variant of a FG model) and the catching-up of less developed nations (Akamatsu\u2019s second variant of a FG model). Changes in the structure of a nation\u2019s trade flows basically reveal shifts of that nation\u2019s role in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b38414cd-fd48-436a-b3c5-15b727f1fc06": {"__data__": {"id_": "b38414cd-fd48-436a-b3c5-15b727f1fc06", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "05438ca165612f599f227b7a6b4468e21429f36a3b2fc7e4d42e2ce0d93516b6"}, "3": {"node_id": "96c37ad8-b044-45e9-a9c5-718de28ea3fd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "372cac03af57f6129f5a06de166056af50eecdcddb3ed12dfdf59cf07a726ad5"}}, "hash": "1117a6fe2813c9c0b0d4e20893d54b81d0832b892c157b025cccc2456c98f75e", "text": "the regional division of labour. To analyze these patterns, we aim to demonstrate a dynamic picture of the countries of interest over time using our own empirical method. Our method is built upon methods that have been used earlier in the literature to verify a potential pattern of FG framework (see Box 3.1). Box 3.1 Empirical methods used in earlier research A widespread method used in earlier studies is the calculation of the revealed comparative advantage (RCA) index. RCA measures the relative strength of a country in exports of certain products, which can be defined as the ratio of export share of each sector in total exports of the country to the share of exports of that good in world exports. In a FG context, RCA is used to rank countries according to their degree of comparative advantage and to identify the shifts in comparative advantage of countries in a region. Another common method is based upon the co-variations between FDI and RCAs, which helps to ana- lyze the role of FDI as a channel to recycle comparative advantage. Dowling and Cheang (2000) asked whether the industry\u2019s share of FDI was linked or matched with the RCA vectors of that industry. Authors provided evidence for the validity of the FG framework pattern for 1970-1995 by comparing the Spearman rank correla- tion coefficients between the RCA vectors of countries, or groups of countries, for the years 1970, 1985, and 1995. An analysis of the relative specialization of the countries in the region in three industries \u2014 computer, electronics, and textile and clothing \u2014 show rankings consistent with a FG pattern. Their results indicate Japan to be the leading country, followed by the NIEs, which are in turn followed by the ASEAN-4. The FDI patterns 3. Empirical analysis and assessments 8 Sequential move of labor-intensive industries from a relatively advanced country to a relatively disadvantaged one is termed by Ozawa (2005) as \u201cmarket recycling\u201d or \u201crecycling of comparative advantage.\u201d 17 in the region revealed that they reflect recycling of comparative advantage8 as suggested by the FDI-based FG framework. Likewise, Cutler et al. (2003) provided confirming evidence for a FG pattern of development, exploring the labour-intensive sectors\u2019 trade patterns among Japan, the NIEs, and the ASEAN-4. Based upon our discussions on empirical testing of the FG pattern, the method we choose must be able to provide a dynamic description of the shifts of countries within the region\u2019s structure of division of labour, which will then enable us with a metric to order the ranks of the countries as suggested by the FG pattern, i.e., the leading goose and the latecomer or group of latecomer geese. One such method along these lines is introduced by Kwan (2002). He analyzes product characteristics classified based upon their sophistica- tion levels. Product sophistication depicts both the product\u2019s and the economy\u2019s advancement level (as a weighted average of all product sophistications); and by ordering the development levels of the countries in terms of their export structure9 this method proves to be useful to trace the sequential ordering of individual countries, as in a FG formation. Our empirical analysis starts with the calculation of sophistication indices both at the sectoral and national levels. We then construct distribution of product sophistications (SPs) for individual countries, fol- lowing Kwan (2002).10 His method has two stages. One is the calculation of the level of sophistication indices of the traded products, i.e., SP. The other is the development of an index for the country by calculating the weighted average of the overall sophistication indices of exported products of the country,11 i.e., country sophistication (SC).12 If a single country is a part of the FG pattern of development, in our framework one would expect to see an improvement of SC over time as it moves forward in the FG formation. The pattern of SC is first rapidly moving up and then slowing down as the SC reaches a particular level of sophistication. At low levels of sophistication increasing SC might be much easier to achieve in comparison to high sophistication levels. In a very crude way, we would expect to see this change as an extended S-shaped curve, which maps an individual country\u2019s SC over time (Figures 3.1a).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "96c37ad8-b044-45e9-a9c5-718de28ea3fd": {"__data__": {"id_": "96c37ad8-b044-45e9-a9c5-718de28ea3fd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"T