stics and their shares in total produc- tion, trade, and investment, respectively. However, our focus here will be mainly on trade structure. Note that the scope of this paper puts particular emphasis on shifts in the regional division of labor through trade flows. 10 The method used here is a modification of Kwan\u2019s (2002) original method with differences, to be explained in Annex C. 11 For a detailed explanation, see Annex C. 12 For the pros and cons of the Sophistication Indices, see Annex C. 18 3.2 Data and empirical results In order to calculate sophistication indices, we used the UN commodity trade database for the global in- ternational trade flow of each product and the World Development Indicators dataset for per capita GDP (PPP at current US dollars). For product classification, we used the five-digit13 Standard International Trade Classification Revision 3 (SITC rev. 3) series. Our data covers 2,243 manufacturing sectors14 for 162 countries. In order to capture SC changes over the recent decade, we repeat the two-step procedure (see Annex C) for the three years: 1995, 2000, and 2005.15 The main indicator we investigate is the distribution of SCj for individual countries and their dynamic shift over the 10-year period. Our findings confirm the advanced level of the manufacturing exports of Japan; the first-tier and second-tier countries depict a FG-consistent pattern over the period of analysis (Figure 3.2). Japan has the most advanced export structure, with the highest SC level in each year, followed by the first-tier16 countries, the second-tier countries, and China and India. We also observe that there is a significant shift and a faster advancement change in the second-tier\u2019s exports sophistication level in comparison to the first-tier countries, particularly from 1995 to 2000. Figure 3.2 displays a picture consistent with our earlier argument that the sophistication level of a country goes up at an increasing rate during early stages of development and then at a slower pace as the country\u2019s development level increases. Figure 3.3 also shows that the differences in sophistication level among countries shrinks as they climb the development ladder as a result of getting closer to the technology frontier. Figures 3.4a, 3.4b, and 3.4c present the SC evolution of each country over time and illustrates FG-con- sistent patterns, i.e., rank ordering among the countries in general stays the same over the period of analysis, except for a couple of countries. Among the second-tier countries, Malaysia had a lower sophistication level than Thailand in 1995, but achieved a higher sophistication level than Thailand in 2000. Similar improvements were made in Indonesia in 2000 and Viet Nam in 2005 (Figure 3.4b). The Philippines\u2019 sophistication level in 2005 became as high as Indonesia after experiencing a dramatic decline in 2000.17 Nepal\u2019s exports present a 13 UN commodity trade data provides the five-digit series as the highest level of disaggregation in SITC. 14 Industry codes represent following manufacturing industries: SITC 5 - Chemicals and related products (not elsewhere specified); SITC 6 - Manufactured goods classified chiefly by material; SITC 7 - Machinery and transport equipment; STIC 8 - Miscellaneous manufactured articles. Value unit is in current US dollars. We preferred the SITC series since its covers a large number of reporting countries, as well as a longer time series in comparison to other commodity classification. 15 Ideally, it would be better to use the most recent trade data, in order to have the most recent picture as much as possible.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7cd7f163-5b33-42b7-af26-4b8d1198f1b7": {"__data__": {"id_": "7cd7f163-5b33-42b7-af26-4b8d1198f1b7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/