s the share of low sophisticated products declined from 1995 to 2005. Similar to the first-tier countries, the second tier\u2019s export structure also shows a shift towards highly sophisticated goods, though the rate of rise is relatively small in comparison. China\u2019s export structure shows the most dynamic picture as the compositional change in SP distribution is leaning towards high sophisticated goods. Likewise, India\u2019s export structure shows a compositional change with an increase in the shares of highly sophisticated products.19 Figure 3.5b presents SP distributions for the Philippines, Viet Nam, Bangladesh, Cambodia, Mongolia, and Nepal. There are major compositional shifts in product sophistication in the Philippines, Viet Nam, and Mongolia. On the other hand, the Bangladesh and Cambodia export structures are quite stagnant. The export SP level of almost all countries in Figure 3.5b is lower than the world\u2019s 10th percentile sophistication level, which is consistent with their respective position in FG formation. 19 Shares of goods that fall into the range of SPi between the global median SPi and the 90th percentile (Figure 3.5). 23 Figure 3.5a Distribution of product sophistication (SP) Note: Own calculations based upon UN Commodity Trade Database. First Tier Countries China Second Tier Countries India Japan World Exports 24 Figure 3.5b Distribution of product sophistication (SP) Note: Own calculations based upon UN Commodity Trade Database. Philippines Viet Nam Bangladesh Cambodia Nepal Mongolia 25 An important question is whether the export structural changes of the more advanced countries allow new opportunities for the late comers. In other words, do the declining shares of low sophisticated products in the exports of the first and second-tier countries and of China and India reflect their graduation from these industries? The answer to this question is not only significant in terms of what it says about the potential for the latecomers but it also might provide some information on possible challenges posed by emerging China and India. A good way to approach this question is by looking at the change in a country\u2019s market share in the world. In this section, we consider those goods with SP levels less than 25,000. Goods falling within this SP range are primarily those with declining shares in the leading economies, which also correspond mostly to low value-added, low-technology, and labour-intensive products. Figure 3.6 shows the following results: \uf06c Except for India and China, there exists evidence that both first and second-tier countries are losing their market share in world exports of goods with low SP levels\u2014a finding consistent with the FG pattern. The degree of the losses depends on the peculiar features of each economy. \uf06c Japan\u2019s export figures confirm systematic declines over the years in its share of all low-sophisticated products. \uf06c China\u2019s share of exports shows a rising trend in almost all product categories except for those at the very low end. \uf06c The extent of the increases in China\u2019s share in global exports depicts a positive correlation between the shares and the level of sophistication of the products. Despite the compositional shift in China\u2019s export structure in favor of more sophisticated products, Chinese firms show basically no sign of moving out of low-sophisticated exports. Rather, Chinese firms have increased their export share in all types of low- sophisticated products. It would be unjust to expect China to follow exactly the same transformations experienced in the lead- ing economies, given its unique size and nature. Nevertheless, its rising share of all products in the world market gives us some hint about the possibilities for other developing nations in the region with respect to a revamped FG pattern in the near future. One can simply argue that if any FG pattern can somehow be sustained, shifts in Chinese exports towards more sophisticated goods will most probably take a much lon- ger time as compared to earlier experiences of the leaders in the region. Such peculiarities of the Chinese economy do certainly matter for the FG pattern of development. Similar to China, India\u2019s exports of low-sophisticated products have increased, even though the extent of the rise is negligible compared to China. Further, India shows no sign of moving away from such low- sophisticated products. A more dynamic upward shift in Indian exports can be observed in products ranging between SP 15,000 and 20,000, including the manufacturing of textile yarn, fabrics, apparel and clothing accessories, and nonferrous metals.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6197798e-6354-4d7a-96be-586e2284b783": {"__data__": {"id_": "6197798e-6354-4d7a-96be-586e2284b783", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d2b0129eca2ef39f4b2eb8fe31d9036763f7114b624b557f85ef8d5684f351e5"}, "2": {"node_id": "db99c955-8c6e-44e5-b656-01eb5bb3bd73", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fdb8df0dc2a94ae16e0fa03b53906d51c121d030e84a2598095cf8640ec84e3c"}}, "hash": "4a215134360ee1e2a8ce0579aa7a1ed0bc958f516ec472e0d3fa708eb2d14c8e", "text": "Overall, our findings on China and India suggest that there is little optimism for such countries as Bangladesh, Cambodia, Nepal, and Mongolia, whose almost entire export structure are comprised of low- sophisticated products. However, caution is required in interpreting this conclusion. An exploration", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f738d6d0-a38c-49e6-ae38-7a5cabe191e8": {"__data__": {"id_": "f738d6d0-a38c-49e6-ae38-7a5cabe191e8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "55d495b8bb0692982d946898a96620aad27b7953a63f1aeae1a1dc3ec44f3ea3"}}, "hash": "55d495b8bb0692982d946898a96620aad27b7953a63f1aeae1a1dc3ec44f3ea3", "text": "of the import structures of China and India is required in order to rule out a possible third scenario, which we might call the \u201ctrading hub.\u201d An economy becomes a trading hub when both imports and exports show rising shares in world trade; that is, if it imports the products it exports. 26 Figure 3.6 Distribution of product sophistication (SPi < 25,000) Japan China India First Tier Countries India (SP>10,000 & SP<25,000) Second Tier Countries Note: Own calculations based upon UN Commodity Trade Database. 27 In this section we will make use of our empirical results summarized in the previous section to derive possible opportunities for cooperative regional integration. We will also draw attention to some challenges that could be faced particularly by relatively less developed countries with respect to the emerging players in the region. These possibilities and challenges are presented below, following each of the \u201cfacts\u201d that we have discussed earlier in this study. Fact 1. Country sophistication (SC) indices show a FG-consistent pattern when the sophistication curve of the exports of each country/country-group is S-shaped and when the dynamic picture of the distribution of so- phistication indices of exports shows a rising share of highly sophisticated goods while shares of low sophisticated goods decline. Do neighboring developing countries have to worry about the upward shift of sophistication indices in emerging economies? The pace at which advanced countries move away from products that require relatively lower levels of capital intensification and technology does matter. The number of years that would be left to the successors to produce and export low-capital and low-tech commodities plays a significant role in deter- mining the economic outcome for the rest of the region. Whether or not the advanced economies abandon the jump-start industries completely while climbing the sophistication curve is another issue; this has been debated ever since Akamatsu\u2019s original contribution. For instance, researchers have found that even Japan has not moved out of labour-intensive industries entirely (Bernard and Ravenhill 1995). Clearly, the evolution of climbing the sophistication curve depends on several factors, some of which are exogenous to the production and trade structure of an economy and some of which are endogenous. While identification of each factor might not be easy, some factors are evident from earlier research. For example, the geographical size of a country or other spatial conditions is a crucial determinant of the nature of a country\u2019s production and trade structure. Effective industrial and/or trade policies at all levels are also instrumental in making a difference in shifting the role of each economy in the regional division of labour. With respect to the pace of the evolution, the rate at which Japan or the first-tier countries changed their place in the regional division of labour might not be applicable for China or India. One underlying reason is the sheer size of their economies, including their labour pool. Tung (2003) points to a possible disruption in the FG pattern of development if certain latecomers have become new leaders in the region but remain too long in low-technology industries. In the case of China, for instance, the relocation of labour-intensive low value-added production might take a much longer time due to the large labour pool in the interior of the country and restrictions on labour migration between regions. The urban/rural divide as well as coastal/ inland divide indicates that the FG formation may not appear rapidly not only in labour-intensive industries but in other industries as well. In addition to physical regional dualities, social dualities make any discussion of China or India as one country extremely difficult. For instance, Feng (2007) describes China as one country yet three people: urbanities, migrants, and peasants \u2014 groupings that determine the boundaries of inequality 4. Opportunities and challenges for cooperative regional integration in Asia 28 in China. Such inequalities warn us to be cautious when one considers the process of industrial upgrading or shifts in production only within an economic perspective. Social constructs play a significant role both on the nature and speed of the process. Despite these observations, it is still possible to identify opportunities for developing neighbors when China and India join the group of leaders. First, Chinese exports do not affect each and every developing economy in the region. Some argue that manufacturing goods exports would be affected negatively all over the world with a rise of China, but Hanson and Robertson (2007), for example, have counter-argued that had China\u2019s export supply capacity been constant over the period 1996-2003, demand for exports would have been 0.6 to 1.4 percent higher in the 10 developing countries studied.20 Thus, even", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9d82aebf-92c9-4059-a5d0-4e5e16f8a813": {"__data__": {"id_": "9d82aebf-92c9-4059-a5d0-4e5e16f8a813", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8bd76ea539d889958f2f12f422dbdf82d35c6a63262215c494d82653b84e12a3"}, "3": {"node_id": "822fc1b3-211e-41c7-8283-b4f30fa7c93f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bbe7a7210386d31fcfa2a6f31106ba7b8bdefc94306b6978f7d30af858b1d4f5"}}, "hash": "1617bdf63fa953b960f3c6cdeedfaef6ab71503c2ed5c4c99fc513ae4c3eb6f3", "text": "for countries most special- ized in export manufacturing and that are expected to be adversely influenced by China\u2019s export growth, China\u2019s expansion signifies only a moderate negative shock. Second, Roland-Holst, Verbiest, and Zhai (2005) argue against the claim that Chinese growth crowds out other developing neighbors\u2019 economic growth. The authors found that the recent acceleration of China\u2019s and India\u2019s growth process brought rapid growth across the region. It has also been argued that should the two economies grow fast, then their trade grows very fast and their mutual trade becomes a major part of world trade. As a result, mutual growth forms a motivation for forming links and affinities between two econo- mies. With further trade expansion they would grow even faster. Third, besides raising the region\u2019s export competitiveness, emerging China and India also form a new basis for Asian regional growth as their domestic demand for consumption increase. Roland-Holst, Verbi- est, and Zhai (2005) claim that over the last decade China\u2019s growth has become a driving force for regional growth and development. They suggest that as these two economies proceed and expand in tandem, they will provide growth leverage both for their neighbors and for economies elsewhere through a web of supply chains. In this process, they also predict that ASEAN economies will form a growth bridge between the two emerging markets and that growth externalities will be transferred to slower growing economies. Cambodia, Lao PDR, Myanmar, and Viet Nam, among others, are likely to benefit from this dynamic growth, leading to a convergence in Asia. In order to examine who might benefit more from increasing demands in China and India we analyze the imports of the two emerging economies to see whether there is any shift in the structure of their imports from a country or country group in Asia compared to the world. Figures 4.1 and 4.2 present an upward and a rightward shift in Chinese and, to some degree, in Indian imports. The shares of relatively high sophisticated imports from the world shifted up. Thus, countries that export such highly sophisticated products (those with sophistication levels above 22,000) are likely to benefit from the growth of these two emerging economies. Within the region, Japan, first-tier, and second-tier economies appear to be the beneficiaries as exporters of relatively high-sophisticated goods. On the other hand, there does not seem much potential for the rest of the region at this moment, particularly for the slow-growing potential successors, given the rising share of China\u2019s and India\u2019s exports and their declining imports of goods with low levels of sophistication (see Figure 3.6). The distributions tell us that opportunities are available more for exporters of higher levels of sophistication; for instance, the Philippines and Viet Nam. These two developing nations appear to have benefited most from rising China and India over the last decade, and this pattern might persist in the near future as well. What can be done in order to benefit fully from the growth process of China and India? As Roland-Holst, Verbiest, and Zhai (2005) point out, developing nations should consider the improvement of trade facilitation and underlying framework which drives regional integration and growth. Scholars have raised attention to a lack of an institutional base similar to an Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) in Asia. The Asian Economic Community (AEC) has been proposed as an example to provide a more robust 20 The authors identified 10 developing economies for which manufacturing represents more than 75 percent of merchandise exports: Hungary, Malaysia, Mexico, Pakistan, the Philippines, Poland, Romania, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Turkey. 29 China\u2019s Imports - World China\u2019s Imports - Japan & First Tier Figure 4.1 Distribution of product sophistication (SP), China\u2019s imports China\u2019s Imports - Second Tier China\u2019s Imports - Rest of the Region Rest of the region includes the following countries: Philip- pines, Viet Nam, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Mongolia, Pakistan, Cambodia, and Nepal. Note: Own calculations based upon UN Commodity Trade Database. 30 regional integration process for ASEAN members and neighboring countries. Kojima (2002) strongly recom- mends AEC to take initiatives to promote regional economic development and help make the AEC region an important center for global economic growth.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "822fc1b3-211e-41c7-8283-b4f30fa7c93f": {"__data__": {"id_": "822fc1b3-211e-41c7-8283-b4f30fa7c93f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8bd76ea539d889958f2f12f422dbdf82d35c6a63262215c494d82653b84e12a3"}, "2": {"node_id": "9d82aebf-92c9-4059-a5d0-4e5e16f8a813", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1617bdf63fa953b960f3c6cdeedfaef6ab71503c2ed5c4c99fc513ae4c3eb6f3"}}, "hash": "bbe7a7210386d31fcfa2a6f31106ba7b8bdefc94306b6978f7d30af858b1d4f5", "text": "His proposal is also crucial in order to coordinate a rapid regional development as described by the FG model. In contrast to other existing core economic units, such as the North American Free Trade Agreement, AEC\u2019s regional integration should focus on promoting economic development while harmonizing unilateral trade regulations and achieving open regionalism. Kojima (2000) also suggested \u201cagreed specialization\u201d as the third pillar of the FG model in order to create opportunities for", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ed694c28-62e7-4e88-a8e3-87352d597c24": {"__data__": {"id_": "ed694c28-62e7-4e88-a8e3-87352d597c24", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1667a4162052fe1bfab17e06dfbfd900314a348494cd7175040b7069697359ab"}, "3": {"node_id": "599c704c-da93-483e-a756-048968ce9cd8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "470b41fcc418aa81e38359848a9b783fc6ebf7326949b6d453c16c42edcb8a3b"}}, "hash": "8868b9fde83f3d1d7c8665df7b3ba2e4e8f4e590205860a0265b33b705c2c8f9", "text": "all countries in the region. Recent industrialization processes in almost all developing nations in the region have led to a shift towards intra-industry trade. Agreed specialization opens up new possibilities when inter-industry trade has reached its limits; and it also supports pro-trade FDI, which is the second pillar of Kojima\u2019s theory. What matters, as mentioned earlier, is whether such an agreed specialization among nations is feasible or not. It is certainly a valid solution in theory; however, when considered within the context of state business and today\u2019s complicated production network nexus, one can easily see that it is un- likely to mobilize common interests on the agreed specialization at the national level. Historical evidence tells us that, other than the Soviet Bloc economies, agreed specialization among nations has not yet happened. Nevertheless, there is still a significant role for regional trade agreements (RTAs) and bilateral trade agreements (BTAs) in the facilitation of agreed specialization to some degree. As proposed by Memi\u015f and Figure 4.2 Distribution of product sophistication (SP), India\u2019s imports India\u2019s Imports - Japan & First-tier China\u2019s Imports - World India\u2019s Imports - Second-tier India\u2019s Imports - Rest of the Region Note: Own calculations based upon UN Commodity Trade Database. 31 Montes (2006), any trade agreement at the regional or bilateral level can be evaluated considering the pos- sible positive and/or negative impacts on industrial development from a FG-type development perspective, rather than the standard static approaches usually implemented. The focus of these agreements should not be narrowly settled on only the expansion of trade, but rather on a variety of other developmental dimensions as suggested by the FG pattern of development. In this study we propose a dynamic tool for examining country sophistication through an examination of the country\u2019s export and import structure. The framework introduced can be utilized in evaluating the affects of any change in trade regulations by comparing the ex-ante and ex-post profiles of trade structures within a single country or across nations region wide. Fact 2. Over the last two decades the structure of production has become more a part of international production networks through fragmentation as well as agglomeration, which might provide a scope for FG forma- tion. This transition has had an important impact on the patterns of trade both within a single country as well as in a regional context with respect to the regional division of labour. For instance, Wagle (2007) discusses the linkages between product fragmentation and trade integration intensively looking at the Asian countries, showing how fragmentation and trade integration spur the two pillars of growth \u2014 trade and FDI \u2014 in the region. Starting with low-tech labour-intensive industries, many countries\u2019 production, particularly in East Asia, has shifted towards more sophisticated goods. This process has happened not only in the electronics sector but corresponds to a wide range of goods, from cars to footwear. Wagle (2007) points out that between 1990 and 2000 trade in parts and components grew at an annual rate of 9.1 percent, which is faster than the annual growth of world merchandise trade (6.5 percent) and world output (3.7 percent). East Asia\u2019 s share in the production of parts and components for offices, machinery, telecommunications, and motor vehicles accounts for over two-thirds of total export in these sectors during the 1990s. These sectors are also shown as the most dynamic of all export sectors. As long as the less technologically sophisticated economies can reap the benefits from being part of these dynamic international networks and facilitate reinvestment of the profits in other domestic industries, fragmentation can be a well-suited system. Should the institutional settings be such to as provide available opportunities through the sound interaction of market forces among states, for instance, a trade policy, a good industrial policy, and the fragmentation of production processes can confer possible gains for all. Nevertheless, caution is required in concluding that fragmentation is good without any conditionality. The challenges are vast for the economies hosting the production of low value-added parts and pieces of the final good produced. Being locked into the labour-intensive phases of production may result in investors\u2019 perception of the host countries as low-wage labour reserves. Hence, unless participating in international production network facilitates job creation and capital formation and strengthens the balance of payments of that economy, the value-added created in such activities is usually transferred to outside the host country through the operations of multinational firms.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "599c704c-da93-483e-a756-048968ce9cd8": {"__data__": {"id_": "599c704c-da93-483e-a756-048968ce9cd8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1667a4162052fe1bfab17e06dfbfd900314a348494cd7175040b7069697359ab"}, "2": {"node_id": "ed694c28-62e7-4e88-a8e3-87352d597c24", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implic