t but, more specifically, how much of the final value-added of their operations contributes to growth, productivity, and its sustainability. Fact 3. If the FG framework is to be exploited, trade might become more of a two-way trade type providing a cooperative interdependence among economies. As a result of the penetration of product fragmentation in the production systems and growth through industrialization, trade has become more of an intra-industry rather than inter-industry trade. Rising intra-region or intra-group trade among the first and second-tier countries supports this third fact. Industries in lower-income countries have become integrated with those in advanced societies, evolving 32 through a convergence process. Debates on the relationship between intra-industry trade and the growth of trade suggest that there is a positive relation between the two, i.e., trade expands more in the presence of intra-industry trade. Countries benefit from trade expansion as long as trade-induced efficiencies provide the needed resources for industrial upgrading. Industrial upgrading, on the other hand, is possible if the industry ladder is not blocked for the successor economy. Historical evidence tells us that we should not downplay the role of public policy. Both empirical evidence, as well as theoretical framework of the FG model in its original form, suggests positive impacts of public policies. One cannot dismiss the fact that a robust domestic economy with its external trade policy depends particularly on achievements in social development (Memi\u015f and Montes 2005). Import-substitution industrialization, that is, reducing imports of industrialized products through local production of those prod- ucts, has been an essential phase of the convergence process. Whether this process evolves at a faster pace or not depends on exploiting a FG framework that is aligned with an appropriate industrial and social policy framework. Even though trade-centered development is necessary for a FG pattern of development, it cannot be sufficient if not supported by the latter. Since industrial upgrading, innovation, technological capacity, and human capabilities are interwoven with each other in a FG pattern of development, social, industrial, or trade related policies cannot be taken as totally separate factors. Rather, all three policies should be considered within an inclusive holistic structure. The opportunities are immense, even more so when the nature of trade is of the intra-industry type. Yet the challenge is obvious: Success depends on an integrated framework that combines trade, industrial, and social policy together within a human development perspective. Fact 4. The FG formation could induce more free trade agreements (FTAs). A proliferation of bilateral FTAs has already intensified regional integration in Asia over the last two decades. As of 2007 there have been 300 FTAs negotiated globally, 119 of which have been implemented in the Asia-Pacific region since 2002. China has been a major driving force in these negotiations; there are almost 30 countries with which China is negotiating or has proposed an FTA. 21 FG presupposes a regional development scenario through the flow of trade and investment. Thus FTAs that are in accord with the essence of the FG pattern could play a crucial role in regional development. There are two broad categories of FTAs: South-South and North-South. The former involves negotiations among developing countries while the latter corresponds to the negotiations between an advanced economy and a developing economy or group of developing economies (Khor 2007). FTAs offer both potential costs and benefits to developing countries.22 One obvious benefit is market access, which is particularly crucial for land- locked countries. In addition, FTAs, through FDI, enhance the possibilities of investment flows and technology transfers. Evaluations of FTAs within a FG context should consider the possible positive and/or negative impacts on industrial development at the sectoral level. Assessments on the changes in trade volume that ignore industrial transformation through domestic or foreign investment are incomplete and do not capture the synergies among trade, investment, and development, which have important implications for the FG pattern of development in a regional context (Memi\u015f and Montes 2006). Nevertheless, FTAs should be approached with caution. Questions arise about whether new integra- tion arrangements promote trade or lead to trade diversion, and whether they support social development or bring social exclusions and tensions. Social costs come along with any type of economic transformation, and FTAs usually act as an accelerator of this process. Thus, with regards to employment policy, attention is needed to ensure a socially cohesive progress and an approach to free trade in its larger context. 21 See www.bilaterals.org/ for more detailed information. 22 See Khor (2007) for an extended discussion on possible costs and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "adf34d9f-6394-44f8-b72e-c1513b21ed4a": {"__data__": {"id_": "adf34d9f-6394-44f8-b72e-c1513b21ed4a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-co